Some people tend to think of books almost as "demons" that "possess" the reader, enchanting him into some new belief or idea. I guess this explains the "ideological" type of man, who is prone to political enthusiasm, makes rash jumps e.g. from fascism to anarchist systems often.

Like I've seen people talk about wanting to basically go Werwolf mode in the woods or start a new Colonia Dignidad, then in a few months get emotional over "the dignity of migrants" and mention random Marx quotes, all without any irony or pause. Just a total lack of discernment.

Dr. Peat talking about his trip to the Southern States in 1960 and how some locals wanted him dead just because they didn't like his appearance (sideburns, an unconventional clothes, etc.) reminds me of how an older friend was stalked by an insane person one night on the streets.

I've been told that in the barracks, after conscription, the dumbest and most vulgar soldiers always are attracted to attack and torture the "intellectual" ones. It's like a parody of opposites attracting each other. The ugly ones tend to pick trouble with the handsome, etc.

In such situations it is just the "demonic" aspect that is invoked and drives the compulsion for violence, because the merely "animal" naturally is soothed by virtue, which is why St. Jerome had a pet lion, St. Seraphim of Sarov with the bear, etc. Nature submits to super-nature.

I understand the importance of border stones, boundary markers, etc. and the Roman punishment of death of one who illegitimately tried to move one, because part of our village property is technically on public land and my grandpa went to war with government and neighbors over it.

The end part of our garden is fenced out of the rest of the land, a heavy metal gate connecting the two. My grandfather planted trees in the enclave before he passed away. That small piece of land is my birthright. I would enter a shootout over it. The law of blood makes it mine.

Etruscan afterlife and ancestral worship was deindividualized, impersonal. The living did not love the dead and the dead did not love the living. It consisted in treating the dissolved spirits of one's ancestors as a demon to wield. Can be characterized as chthonic, telluric.

The Roman concept was heroic, salubrious, a triumphant ancestor reignited with every generation. Not an abstraction, but a bright force that acts to bring luck, greatness, "acting in the sense of a salute". It comes from above, brings healthfulness, invigorates, bolsters, boosts.
